unlekker.mb2.geo
Class UVertexList

java.lang.Object
  unlekker.mb2.util.UMB
      unlekker.mb2.geo.UVertexList
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Iterable<UVertex>, UConst
public class UVertexList
extends UMB
implements java.lang.Iterable<UVertex>

Auto-growing list of UVertex objects that are internally stored as an ArrayList.. The default behavior is to add vertices by copy rather than reference, without checking for duplicate vertices. This is convenient for most cases but can cause problems for per-vertex transformations and STL output. Adding by reference can be activated by calling enable(NOCOPY);, duplicate checking is activated by enable(NODUPL); TODO - NODUPL / NOCOPY is not consistently implemented.

Author:
marius

sortAsPolygon

public UVertexList sortAsPolygon()

Returns a new UVertexList containing the UVertex instances from this list, sorted by the angle between each vertex and the centroid. The result should be a valid polygon. The sorting is done in 2D in the XY plane.

Code based on solution by Daniel Shiffman, http://www.shiffman.net.

Returns:

isClockwise

public boolean isClockwise()

Determines the winding order of this vertex list by calculating the area of the polygon it represents.Only works in the XY plane. The area calculation is Area = Area + (X2 - X1) * (Y2 + Y1) / 2).

Code by Jonathan Cooper, found at http://forums.esri.com/Thread.asp?c=2&f=1718&t=174277#513372.

public UVertexList calcDelta()

Returns:

calcDelta

public UVertexList calcDelta(float damping)
Produces a new UVertexList containing the delta vector for each position in this list, so that for a given index==[0..n-2] the delta equals get(index+1).copy().sub(get(index));

For index==n-1 the delta is the same as for index==n-2. The damping parameters causes damping between the previous and current delta, so that the previous value is weighted by (1.0-damping) and the new value by damping. This is useful to "slow down" changes in the heading along a path.

Parameters:
damping -
Returns:

smooth

public static UVertexList smooth(UVertexList in,
                                 int smoothLevel)

Smooths a list of vertices, with the number of smoothing iterations specified by smoothLevel.

The algorithm consists of taking line segments (v1,v2) from the input vertex list, calculating two new vertices interpolated at 33% and 66% (respectively, v1.lerp(0.33f,v2) and v1.lerp(0.66f,v2) along each segment. The new points are added to a new list, omitting the original vertices.

If the input list is closed (UVertexList.isClosed()==true), the first and last segments are handled so that the interpolation "wraps", if not the original first and last vertices are added to the new list.

Parameters:
in -
smoothLevel -
Returns:

deltaVectors

public UVertexList deltaVectors()
Returns new UVertexList containing a list of the delta vectors for each vertex in the current list (calculated by deltaN=this.get(N+1).sub(this.get(N)) etc.) Since there is no valid delta vector for the last position in the list, a copy of the delta vector for the penultimate position is given instead.

Returns:

deltaVectors

public UVertexList deltaVectors(float damper)
Returns new UVertexList containing a list of the delta vectors for each vertex in the current list. Values are dampened (interpolated) with the value of the previous vertex as specified by the damper parameter, providing control of the rate of change. The calculation is given by deltaN=this.get(N+1).sub(this.get(N)).mult(damper).add(deltaPrev.copy().mult(1-damper));.

Parameters:
damper -
Returns:

hasDuplicates

public boolean hasDuplicates()

removeDupl

public UVertexList removeDupl(boolean doDelete)
Removes or "fixes" duplicate vertices in the list as identified by the UVertex.equals() method. doDelete controls how duplicates are handled: If doDelete==true, only the first instance is retained while additional duplicates are deleted from the list. This ensures that the list contains only unique vertices, but may alter the list length and order. If doDelete==false, objects representing duplicate entries are replaced by an object reference to the first matching instance in the list. Vertex order and length of list is preserved, but subsequent changes to any reference to duplicate entry will affect all entries as well, as they now point to a single object. This is useful for consistent STL export (where rounding errors can cause identical vertices to become non-identical).

Parameters:
doDelete - Flag indicating whether duplicates should be deleted or replaced by a reference to a single instance.
Returns:
